WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.942 --> 00:00:07.900
GRAHAM ALLISON: So thanks
very much for coming.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:11.020
And I look forward to
a lively discussion.

00:00:14.030 --> 00:00:17.210
I was-- I guess
this is the 13th day

00:00:17.210 --> 00:00:19.340
of the rollout of the new book.

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:23.860
It's called "Destined for War:
Can America and China Escape

00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:25.270
Thucydides' Trap?"

00:00:25.270 --> 00:00:27.460
I was out on the
West Coast last week,

00:00:27.460 --> 00:00:29.590
actually did an event
in Silicon Valley

00:00:29.590 --> 00:00:33.405
with the Andreesen
Horowitz folks, to which

00:00:33.405 --> 00:00:35.500
some Google people came.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:39.670
And I mentioned at the
event that basically I'm

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:43.510
a big fan of Silicon
Valley, and it's even more--

00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:47.410
it's Boston based equivalents,
since this is where I live,

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:51.820
and the ways in which you're
blowing my mind almost

00:00:51.820 --> 00:00:54.280
every day, or every
week, or every month,

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:56.560
with products that I
couldn't have imagined,

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:58.930
of which Google is
kind of a poster child.

00:00:58.930 --> 00:01:02.920
But I hope that what I'm going
to do in the next 20 minutes

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:06.040
is expand your mind a
little bit about some things

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:07.730
that you may not
have thought about,

00:01:07.730 --> 00:01:10.660
but that which
are likely to have

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:16.610
great consequence for your lives
and for actually your activity.

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:20.380
So most of you are too young
to imagine that there could

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:23.440
be wars between great powers.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.960
I teach at Harvard, as
I've done for a long time.

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:30.430
Students say, well no, no,
that's a last century thing.

00:01:30.430 --> 00:01:32.980
It's been seven decades
since World War II

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:36.340
without great power
war, so great power wars

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:41.140
have been consigned to the
dustbin of history, move on.

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:46.160
To which the answer is
that's historically ignorant.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:52.070
And this seven decade
without great power war

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:55.041
is historically an anomaly.

00:01:55.041 --> 00:01:56.540
Indeed there's a
great essay written

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:59.060
by a Yale historian,
John Gaddis,

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:04.340
about the so-called long
peace, and how anomalous it is.

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:08.330
So before I'm done, I hope
I will have persuaded you

00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:11.030
that if that's what you
thought when you came in,

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:14.510
you should think again, that
wars between great powers

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:18.650
are possible, maybe even a
lot more possible than you

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:20.360
would have imagined.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:23.510
And if there were to
be a great power war,

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:26.209
your lives will
change fundamentally.

00:02:26.209 --> 00:02:28.250
What you're working on
will change fundamentally.

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:30.500
What you're thinking about
will change fundamentally.

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:33.120
You might even be drafted to
have to go fight somewhere

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.070
where you wouldn't like to be.

00:02:35.070 --> 00:02:36.940
And if that seems
incredible, you

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:39.650
should try to think
back 100 years ago.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:41.660
I think one of the
ways of locating

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:45.230
yourself is to think what was
going on 100 years ago today,

00:02:45.230 --> 00:02:47.270
or this month.

00:02:47.270 --> 00:02:51.710
A hundred years ago,
Europe was consumed

00:02:51.710 --> 00:02:55.820
by the first great
war, a war that

00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:58.730
was so devastating
that at the end of it,

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:00.740
historians felt
obliged to create

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:03.530
an entirely new category.

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:06.050
That's why if you Google
it, it says World War,

00:03:06.050 --> 00:03:09.716
and it's was called World War I.

00:03:09.716 --> 00:03:13.070
Now World War I was not
just that it encompassed

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:15.830
so many people and
so many countries,

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:19.400
but that it was so
ultimately devastating.

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:22.730
At the end of it, about 25
million people had perished.

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:24.230
And the Americans
actually had just

00:03:24.230 --> 00:03:30.254
entered World War I two
months ago, in April of 1970.

00:03:30.254 --> 00:03:31.670
So you can go back
and look at it,

00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:33.711
and think a little bit
about it, and think, well,

00:03:33.711 --> 00:03:36.790
what if I were living in 1970.

00:03:36.790 --> 00:03:38.180
What would I be thinking about?

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:39.740
What would be my orientation?

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.180
What would I be
having to work on?

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:43.170
What [INAUDIBLE]?

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:45.350
So in any case, that's
the big picture.

00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:50.760
This is about China,
and the US, and today.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:54.170
And I'm going to do three
questions, three big questions.

00:03:54.170 --> 00:03:56.960
I'll give you three tweet
versions of an answer,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.150
so that you've got the picture.

00:03:59.150 --> 00:04:02.480
And then I'll do a little
elaboration on each.

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:07.400
So first question, what
is the geopolitical event

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:10.850
of your lifetime to date?

00:04:10.850 --> 00:04:13.680
So let's imagine you
were born in 1990,

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:16.829
let's say, a little
after or a little before.

00:04:16.829 --> 00:04:19.290
So over the last 25 years.

00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:23.156
What's the big, big,
big, geopolitical event?

00:04:23.156 --> 00:04:25.790
And the tweet
version of the answer

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:27.575
is that it's the rise of China.

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:36.800
The second question, what will
be the geo strategic challenge

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:41.080
for the rest of your
professional life, for today,

00:04:41.080 --> 00:04:44.450
and as far as any eye can see?

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:46.610
And the tweet version
is that that's

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:54.020
the impact of the rise
of China on the US

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:57.170
and the international order
that the US constructed

00:04:57.170 --> 00:05:01.550
in the aftermath of World
War II, and has maintained,

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:03.980
that principally
accounts for the fact

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:09.190
that there's been seven decades
without any great power war.

00:05:09.190 --> 00:05:10.910
So the impact of
the rise of China

00:05:10.910 --> 00:05:13.600
on the US and the
international order.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:16.600
And the third question is
the subtitle of the book,

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:21.800
can America and China
escape Thucydides' trap?

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:24.100
And the answer is--

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:28.580
excuse me for being professorial
real, but that's my job--

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:32.460
no, and yes.

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.690
So what about no?

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:39.790
No-- if we, in the relations
between the US and China,

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:44.020
this year, and next
year, and the year after,

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:48.100
only see business
as usual, then we

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:51.500
should expect history as usual.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:54.980
And history as usual in
this case would be a war

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:57.940
and it would be catastrophic.

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:01.150
And that's pretty plain
for everybody to see.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:03.130
So that's no, OK.

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:07.180
But yes, as the saying
goes, only those

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:12.610
who fail to study history
are condemned to repeat it.

00:06:12.610 --> 00:06:16.630
So we're not required by
some iron law of history

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:20.020
to repeat mistakes that
people made that led them

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:25.880
into World War I. We're not
required to repeat mistakes

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.240
that lead into World War II.

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:32.570
And we can learn from
the cases in which states

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:35.990
have successfully averted
war, lessons that we can

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:38.130
apply in the current instance.

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:42.030
So that's my three tweet
versions, a little bit more

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:43.820
on the lot.

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:46.760
So start with Thucydides.

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:50.360
For most American audiences,
I've been now 13 days

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:50.930
doing this.

00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:52.730
I have a little
bit of experience,

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:56.540
especially for
radio call-in shows.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:59.450
Yes, this is multi-syllabic.

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:02.850
I know that in your Google
efforts to communicate,

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:05.990
you can get people down to a
single syllables, or at least

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:08.010
two.

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:10.350
And yes, it's a mouthful.

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:13.100
And it's a little
difficult to pronounce.

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:17.150
But a group like this should
know who Thucydides is.

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:21.290
If he's not part of your mental
canon, part of your library

00:07:21.290 --> 00:07:23.880
that helps orient you,
you've missed a big thing

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:25.400
and a big opportunity.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:29.420
So just to make sure we all
know how to pronounce his name,

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:33.680
let me remind you,
it's Thu-ci-di-dees--

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:34.250
Thucydides.

00:07:34.250 --> 00:07:36.340
So let's say it
out loud together--

00:07:36.340 --> 00:07:39.510
Thucydides,
Thucydides, Thucydides.

00:07:39.510 --> 00:07:41.240
So you should not
stumble over that.

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:43.820
Yes, multi-syllabic,
yes complicated,

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:46.820
but he should be
somebody you know.

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:50.450
And actually, in
this wonderful world

00:07:50.450 --> 00:07:54.260
today, you can go
download Thucydides

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:58.760
"Great History of the
Peloponnesian War," for free

00:07:58.760 --> 00:08:00.780
and just read the
first 100 pages.

00:08:00.780 --> 00:08:03.340
And if it doesn't knock your
socks off, I'll be surprised.

00:08:03.340 --> 00:08:07.155
I'll be very surprised,
brilliant book.

00:08:07.155 --> 00:08:09.029
Thucydides, who is that?

00:08:09.029 --> 00:08:10.070
Well, you can Google him.

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:15.340
You'll find he was the
founder and father of history.

00:08:15.340 --> 00:08:19.390
So he's the person who defined
the discipline of history,

00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:23.032
which is getting the facts
about what happened right

00:08:23.032 --> 00:08:25.490
so that other people can read
about it them, and learn what

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:28.090
happened, and learn
the lessons from them.

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:32.679
So the founder of history,
he wrote about the conflict,

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:34.630
the competition
and then conflict

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:36.850
between the two
great city-states

00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:41.169
of classical Greece,
Athens and Sparta.

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:45.010
And he wrote most
famously, "It was the rise

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:49.960
of Athens and the fear that
this instilled in Sparta

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.820
that made the war inevitable."

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:56.980
So Thucydides' trap,
which is a term I coined,

00:08:56.980 --> 00:09:02.860
takes Thucydides insight,
and Thucydides' trap says

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:07.520
when a rising power threatens
to displace a ruling power,

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:10.890
basically shit happens--

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:14.500
alarm bells should
sound, danger ahead.

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:19.640
I looked in this book at the
last 500 years of history.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:23.230
And I give you in the appendix
little potted plant versions

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:27.250
of 16 cases, where if you
go to the Thucydides' Trap

00:09:27.250 --> 00:09:30.820
website, which is up
live, we're actually

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:32.800
inviting additional cases.

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:36.370
These are 16 cases
over the last 500 years

00:09:36.370 --> 00:09:39.220
in which a rising power
threatened to displace

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:41.280
a major ruling power.

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:45.040
In 12 of these cases,
the outcome was war.

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:48.850
In four of the cases,
the outcome was no war.

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:51.610
So Thucydides' line
about inevitable,

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:55.060
that's an exaggeration,
that's hyperbole,

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:57.040
exaggeration for the
sake of emphasis.

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:00.370
He just means
likely, very likely.

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:04.240
So 12 of the cases ended
in war, four of the cases

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:05.720
ended in no war.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:09.070
And what the book
does is try to look

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:13.000
at both the failures
and the successes

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.900
for lessons that might
be relevant for us today.

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:21.850
So to think about this dynamic--

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:25.510
actually this came up in
the discussion last week

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:26.950
in Silicon Valley--

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:28.330
I think for you
all, probably you

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:33.400
should think of an
incumbent and a upstart,

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:36.310
a disruptive upstart.

00:10:36.310 --> 00:10:38.320
So what happens?

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:42.700
So basically, a rising
power feels like I'm bigger,

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:48.100
I'm stronger, my interests
deserve more weight.

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:51.690
I deserve more say,
I deserve more sway.

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:53.190
Actually, the
current arrangements

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:56.850
are discriminating against me,
because they were established

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:59.660
before I was even a player.

00:10:59.660 --> 00:11:03.640
So things need to adjust.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:05.090
I'm being confined.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:08.550
So think of Uber and
the taxi industry.

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:14.680
Think of Google when
it was an upstart.

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:16.240
Actually, Google
now is interesting

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:18.670
because, you live on
both sides of this fence.

00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:21.730
You're a upstart in some
domains, where you're

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:25.606
trying to disrupt some
incumbent, and at the same time

00:11:25.606 --> 00:11:26.980
you're looking
over your shoulder

00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:29.590
where you're an
incumbent in some spaces,

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:34.040
finding Baidu or somebody,
coming to see what they can do.

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:37.330
So what does the
ruling power think?

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:43.600
Well, the ruling power
thinks this is natural.

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:47.920
The way things are
it's good, maybe even

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:49.540
the way they should be.

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:52.240
The status quo has
provided an environment

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:55.900
in which actually you, upstart,
have had a chance to grow up.

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:59.430
So we say to the Chinese, quite
reasonably, how in the world

00:11:59.430 --> 00:12:02.320
have you had seven decades
of peace in which you've

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:06.430
had the opportunity to grow in
the manner in which you have?

00:12:06.430 --> 00:12:08.620
I mean, actually, it's
because of us, because

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:10.510
of the order we provided.

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:13.350
You should be grateful.

00:12:13.350 --> 00:12:17.070
But in general, upstarts are
not grateful for the conditions

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:23.760
that the incumbent provided
And in general, the incumbent,

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:26.830
their entreaties don't end
up having that much impact.

00:12:26.830 --> 00:12:29.130
So think about this
as a general dynamic.

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:33.720
Indeed, I even described
it in the book as--

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:34.890
if you can see--

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:39.210
this is a version of
hierarchical dominance systems

00:12:39.210 --> 00:12:41.190
that you can see in
the animal kingdom.

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:44.520
Take for example gorillas,
with an alpha gorilla,

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:47.850
who's the dominant,
and the want to be.

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:50.834
You can even see in
families, as one child

00:12:50.834 --> 00:12:53.250
who's shorter than the other
one, all of a sudden sprouts.

00:12:53.250 --> 00:12:55.530
And pretty soon,
the taller child,

00:12:55.530 --> 00:12:58.620
when they sit down at the
dinner table, talks more,

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:00.870
thinks he has more to say.

00:13:00.870 --> 00:13:03.420
Maybe even wants to discuss
whether the bedrooms have

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:05.899
been appropriately
allocated, who knows what.

