00:18:17.220 --> 00:18:21.410
So in my class at
Harvard, I give people

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:25.070
a quiz with 26 indicators.

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:27.470
This is an abbreviated
version from the book.

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:30.220
So when will China
become number one?

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:36.680
Auto maker, trading nation,
middle class, billionaires,

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:41.709
fastest supercomputer,
AI, primary engine

00:18:41.709 --> 00:18:42.500
of economic growth.

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:44.660
Generally, Harvard
students guessed

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:49.990
2040, 2050, not in my lifetime.

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:54.080
Then I give them a second
chart, which says already.

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:56.840
Basically, all this
already happened.

00:18:56.840 --> 00:18:59.750
Vaclav Havel, who was the
President of the Czech

00:18:59.750 --> 00:19:03.920
Republic, has a great line
that I quote in the book.

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:07.850
He says things have happened
so fast that we have not yet

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:11.630
had time to be astonished.

00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:19.160
So if you have not seen China in
your face, you are not looking.

00:19:19.160 --> 00:19:25.210
If you haven't seen China
in your space, just wait.

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:31.820
Because in every domain, the
Chinese people have awakened,

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:33.680
they are emerging.

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:36.020
They're proud of
what they're doing.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:40.190
And all the lines about,
well, they can only copy,

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:43.970
I would say go look at
Alibaba's pay system.

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:46.640
Only copies, I don't think so.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:48.740
Well, they can only--

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:52.030
go, take your line only,
and go look around.

00:19:52.030 --> 00:19:55.520
And it mainly is because I
think you haven't looked to see.

00:19:55.520 --> 00:19:57.890
This is extremely
creative people.

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:00.590
I think they're emerging
with a lot of enthusiasm.

00:20:00.590 --> 00:20:02.240
They're very hungry.

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:05.030
And I think everywhere,
in every way,

00:20:05.030 --> 00:20:08.090
you're going to see
the impact of China.

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:12.290
So that puts me to the second
question that I started with,

00:20:12.290 --> 00:20:15.050
what's the great geo
strategic challenge?

00:20:15.050 --> 00:20:18.410
And it's the impact,
the impact, of the rise

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:22.580
of China on the US and
the international order.

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:25.550
So I was testifying to the
Senate Armed Services Committee

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:26.390
about this.

00:20:26.390 --> 00:20:31.280
A former student of mine is the
ranking Democrat, Jack Reed.

00:20:31.280 --> 00:20:34.440
And he said, you've got to
make this simple, very simple.

00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:36.830
So I sent him 10 pages.

00:20:36.830 --> 00:20:39.440
And he said, no, simple, simple.

00:20:39.440 --> 00:20:40.520
I sent him five pages.

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:41.720
He said, nope.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:42.995
So I finally did a cartoon.

00:20:46.410 --> 00:20:49.820
So this is a seesaw.

00:20:49.820 --> 00:20:56.290
I imagine, this is now 2004.

00:20:56.290 --> 00:20:57.744
US is on one end of the seesaw.

00:20:57.744 --> 00:20:58.910
Chinese is on the other end.

00:20:58.910 --> 00:21:02.810
At this point, China's about
20% the size of the US.

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:08.180
2004, excuse me, you were
alive then, even awake, yeah?

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:12.320
2014, China is equal to the US.

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:15.900
2024, substantially larger.

00:21:15.900 --> 00:21:18.260
So, basically, think of
the seesaw just moving.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:23.120
Now in the Obama administration,
the big debate about Asia,

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:25.520
and the thing that President
Obama features actually

00:21:25.520 --> 00:21:30.530
in his swan song about what
was accomplished in the Obama

00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:33.990
foreign policy, was the
so-called pivot to Asia.

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:35.270
You've heard about that.

00:21:35.270 --> 00:21:36.290
So go Google it.

00:21:36.290 --> 00:21:38.660
The pivot to Asia
said we're putting

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:40.160
too much weight
on our left foot,

00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:43.040
in the Middle East, where
we were fighting wars.

00:21:43.040 --> 00:21:45.290
And we need to
lighten there, to put

00:21:45.290 --> 00:21:48.020
more weight on our right
foot, in Asia, where

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:50.210
the future's going to be.

00:21:50.210 --> 00:21:52.580
So there we were
trying to do this.

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:54.260
And I say in the
book, and I think

00:21:54.260 --> 00:21:56.510
this is correct, that all
the time we're arguing about

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:59.750
that, we don't seem to notice
that our feet have just

00:21:59.750 --> 00:22:02.500
lifted off the ground.

00:22:02.500 --> 00:22:05.970
So this is a tectonic
shift in basically

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:08.100
the principal
substructure of power

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:10.040
in the World, economic power.

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:11.600
It's not the only measure.

00:22:11.600 --> 00:22:14.230
I give you a number of
other measures in the book.

00:22:14.230 --> 00:22:15.720
So that's been happening.

00:22:15.720 --> 00:22:22.020
And the impact of that on
China, as it emerges and feels

00:22:22.020 --> 00:22:27.450
its oats, and the US, as
we think, wait a minute,

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:30.840
we are the dominant
power in the world.

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:33.580
We have provided the
international order.

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:35.970
The international
rule-based order

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:38.670
has provided seven
decades of peace.

00:22:38.670 --> 00:22:42.750
China should take its place
in this and be comfortable.

00:22:42.750 --> 00:22:44.190
That's what we say.

00:22:44.190 --> 00:22:47.220
But the Chinese
say, excuse me, we

00:22:47.220 --> 00:22:48.960
have something to
say about this.

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:51.990
We were not consulted when
these rules were written.

00:22:51.990 --> 00:22:54.690
We didn't set the
set of arrangements.

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:57.480
So just to conclude
here, as we see

00:22:57.480 --> 00:23:01.500
the impact of the rise
of China on the US,

00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:05.250
the place where this comes the
closest to coming to a head

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:08.880
is in North Korea today.

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:12.372
So if I were picking a
path from here to war--

00:23:12.372 --> 00:23:13.830
I have a chapter
in the book called

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:16.920
"From Here to War,
Five Scenarios"

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:20.010
to get from where we are
now to a war between--

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:22.800
with thousands of Americans and
Chinese killing each other--

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:27.730
with no leaps, only short
steps, step by step.

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:30.820
But the one that's most
dangerous is North Korea.

00:23:30.820 --> 00:23:33.210
Most of you will
remember that Xi Jinping

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:39.240
met with President Trump in
Mar-a-Lago about six weeks ago.

00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:42.900
At that meeting the principal
message from President Trump

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:47.340
was North Korea is a threat
we are not going to tolerate

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:50.440
and you've got to
solve this problem.

00:23:50.440 --> 00:23:52.020
So what's the issue?

00:23:52.020 --> 00:23:53.670
The issue is as follows.

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:58.260
North Korea, this isolated
impoverished state,

00:23:58.260 --> 00:24:02.610
will, in the months ahead,
not longer than a year or two,

00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:06.900
for sure, test an
ICBM that will allow

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:10.680
it to deliver a nuclear warhead
against San Francisco or Los

00:24:10.680 --> 00:24:12.780
Angeles.

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:15.940
That's hard to believe,
but that's a fact.

00:24:15.940 --> 00:24:18.330
North Korea already can
deliver a nuclear warhead

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:20.340
against Japan.

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:22.710
North Korea can already
delivered a nuclear warhead

00:24:22.710 --> 00:24:24.150
against South Korea.

00:24:24.150 --> 00:24:26.040
So that's already happened.

00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:27.990
That's already a fact.

00:24:27.990 --> 00:24:30.420
So in the months
ahead, it's going

00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:32.805
to conduct tests that
will allow it to deliver,

00:24:32.805 --> 00:24:37.700
or it's somehow going
to be interrupted.

00:24:37.700 --> 00:24:39.800
So when President Trump
first heard of this,

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:42.220
it was in the handoff
between President Obama

00:24:42.220 --> 00:24:43.800
and President-Elect Trump.

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:46.840
Trump said I never heard
of this before in my life.

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:50.460
And the answer, most
Americans haven't.

00:24:50.460 --> 00:24:52.150
But Obama said, I'm
sorry, but that's

00:24:52.150 --> 00:24:54.610
the facts, that's the problem
you're going to have to face.

00:24:54.610 --> 00:25:00.460
Trump went out immediately and
tweeted not going to happen.

00:25:00.460 --> 00:25:02.350
Maybe Obama let
these things happen,

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:04.000
and maybe Bush let
these things happen,

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:08.450
and maybe Clinton let these
things happen, but not Trump.

00:25:08.450 --> 00:25:10.660
This is not going to happen.

00:25:10.660 --> 00:25:14.720
And every day since then, he's
been saying and repeating.

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:19.240
So at the Mar-a-Lago summit,
what he said to Xi Jinping was

00:25:19.240 --> 00:25:22.260
you can solve this problem.

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:24.550
But if you don't
solve this problem,

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:26.660
I can solve this problem.

00:25:26.660 --> 00:25:30.750
But if I do, you're
not going to like it.

00:25:30.750 --> 00:25:34.760
And then he served chocolate
cake at the opening dinner,

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:37.550
excused himself, and
went out and announced

00:25:37.550 --> 00:25:41.450
that the US had launched 50
cruise missiles against Syria,

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:44.450
just in case you
missed the point.

00:25:44.450 --> 00:25:50.030
So can the US deliver cruise
missiles against North Korea

00:25:50.030 --> 00:25:52.700
to prevent it conducting
tests that could launch ICBMs?

00:25:52.700 --> 00:25:54.230
Absolutely.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:25:55.490
Can we do that successfully?

00:25:55.490 --> 00:25:57.000
No question about it.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:01.000
The question is what does
North Korea do in response?

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And the most likely response
would be an attack on Seoul.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.700
They'd kill a million
people in 24 or 48 hours.

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:10.700
Whereupon, the US will
then, with South Korea,

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:13.760
destroy all the additional
artillery and rockets

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:16.520
that could kill even more
people in South Korea.

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:19.370
Whereupon, we have
the second Korean War.

00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:20.874
And most of you
probably don't even

00:26:20.874 --> 00:26:22.790
remember from your history
books what happened

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:23.960
in the first Korean War.

00:26:23.960 --> 00:26:27.950
In the first Korean War,
the US was marching rapidly

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:31.970
towards China's border,
going to unify the country

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:33.920
under South Korea's control.

00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:37.190
The Chinese entered the
world, beat the US back down

00:26:37.190 --> 00:26:39.480
the peninsula to
the 38th parallel,

00:26:39.480 --> 00:26:41.740
which is the
dividing line today.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.450
And in that war, thousands
of Americans and thousands

00:26:44.450 --> 00:26:46.400
of Chinese died.

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:48.560
So could we see a
second Korean War?

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:50.660
I think, God forbid, we could.

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:55.490
Now could you imagine, the
US and China, Trump and Xi,

00:26:55.490 --> 00:26:58.190
sitting down and saying let's
be adults and figure out

00:26:58.190 --> 00:26:59.390
a solution to this problem?

00:26:59.390 --> 00:27:00.890
I think you could.

00:27:00.890 --> 00:27:04.100
But this problem arises in
the context of this Thucydides

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:08.714
dynamic, in which, because
we look at the Chinese

00:27:08.714 --> 00:27:10.130
and think really
what they want is

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:12.120
for us to just be out of here.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:13.680
And that is what they want.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:17.270
I mean, I spent two days doing
a post-mortem on Mar-a-Lago

00:27:17.270 --> 00:27:19.490
with some of the Chinese
and some of the Americans

00:27:19.490 --> 00:27:20.410
who were there.

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:23.120
And they said if
you were not there,

00:27:23.120 --> 00:27:26.400
we wouldn't have this problem.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:28.400
So just leave.

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:29.960
And we say, wait a minute.

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:32.210
South Korea is one of the
most successful countries

00:27:32.210 --> 00:27:33.590
in the world.

00:27:33.590 --> 00:27:35.390
South Korea is a
poster child of what we

00:27:35.390 --> 00:27:37.550
are hoping to see in the world.

00:27:37.550 --> 00:27:38.910
South Korea is a democracy.

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:41.390
South Korea is a market economy.

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:44.160
South Korea has the 13th
largest economy in the world.

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:45.680
It's a fantastic success story.

00:27:45.680 --> 00:27:47.690
We're not going anywhere.

00:27:47.690 --> 00:27:51.830
This is part of the order
that's the order of Asia.

00:27:51.830 --> 00:27:53.755
And if we were to
walk away from there,

00:27:53.755 --> 00:27:56.255
what's going to happen to the
whole international structure?

00:27:56.255 --> 00:27:59.780
So under those
conditions is zero trust.

00:27:59.780 --> 00:28:02.250
Everything, each
thing any party--

00:28:02.250 --> 00:28:05.390
either of the parties
does is misinterpreted.

00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:07.010
So you try to do
something helpful,

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:09.440
and I think you have
an ulterior motive.

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:12.500
And then external
events, like Kim Jong-un

00:28:12.500 --> 00:28:16.760
deciding to launch a
missile, it triggers a set

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:18.680
of actions and reactions
that get people

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:20.360
to where they don't want to go.

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:23.330
So to conclude, what
is the big idea?

00:28:23.330 --> 00:28:26.560
Big idea, Thucydides' trap.

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:28.190
Rising power
threatens to displace

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:32.510
ruling power, basically
serious structural stress that

00:28:32.510 --> 00:28:36.890
allows external events,
or external actors, who

00:28:36.890 --> 00:28:40.160
would otherwise be
inconsequential or easily

00:28:40.160 --> 00:28:45.440
manageable to trigger cascades
of consequences that get you

00:28:45.440 --> 00:28:47.090
to places you don't want to go.

00:28:47.090 --> 00:28:49.370
And the big takeaway
from this is

00:28:49.370 --> 00:28:54.830
we should be serious about
avoiding preventable wars.

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:55.850
If this war happens--

00:28:55.850 --> 00:28:58.340
I pray it won't-- but if a
war between the US and China

00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:03.590
happens in your lifetime, it
will not be because of the iron

00:29:03.590 --> 00:29:04.640
laws of history.

00:29:04.640 --> 00:29:08.150
It will be because of
mistakes that people made.

00:29:08.150 --> 00:29:09.620
And because of
mistakes that they

00:29:09.620 --> 00:29:12.260
make that they
could have avoided.

00:29:12.260 --> 00:29:13.730
So the object of
the book is to try

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:19.430
to help stimulate a great debate
about what we should be doing

00:29:19.430 --> 00:29:22.850
in a more imaginative fashion
to get beyond the business as

00:29:22.850 --> 00:29:25.580
usual, which is how I
characterize what we have been

00:29:25.580 --> 00:29:28.500
doing for the last 20 years.

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:29.730
So that's once over lightly.

00:29:29.730 --> 00:29:35.240
I'm happy to take the arguments
and discussions on all topics.

00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:37.670
AUDIENCE: It seems like
it's easiest to get concrete

00:29:37.670 --> 00:29:39.300
around a specific scenario.

00:29:39.300 --> 00:29:42.860
So it's valuable for you to
have brought up the possibility

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:45.740
of a second Korean War.

00:29:45.740 --> 00:29:48.740
The first Korean War,
as you described it,

00:29:48.740 --> 00:29:52.820
with China having
entered it, and being

00:29:52.820 --> 00:29:55.080
many Americans
and Chinese dying,

00:29:55.080 --> 00:29:59.310
that was not due to
Thucydides' trap, right?

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:02.300
GRAHAM ALLISON: It's just
another war for another set

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:03.560
of dynamics, yes.

00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:07.690
AUDIENCE: So it seems like
there's nothing that--

00:30:07.690 --> 00:30:10.790
the motives would be similar
if it were to happen again.

00:30:10.790 --> 00:30:13.400
And it's not related
to the fact that China

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:15.440
is a growing power, right?

00:30:15.440 --> 00:30:19.880
If the scenario played out
as you say as you said,

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:21.830
that's not because
they're a growing

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:24.390
power and they think they need
to change the world order.

00:30:24.390 --> 00:30:26.810
It's just territorial
issues, the same

00:30:26.810 --> 00:30:29.276
as it would be in the
first Korean War, right?

00:30:29.276 --> 00:30:30.650
GRAHAM ALLISON:
Well, yes and no.

00:30:30.650 --> 00:30:33.900
So I would say it certainly
is a very good question.

00:30:33.900 --> 00:30:35.370
So in the first case--

00:30:35.370 --> 00:30:37.947
just again, for people
that don't remember,

00:30:37.947 --> 00:30:39.530
and you obviously
have read about it--

00:30:39.530 --> 00:30:45.680
but, basically, in
1950, North Korea

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:48.280
attacked South Korea,
just out of the blue.

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:51.200
That the country was divided
where it is currently.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:53.490
North Korea attacked
South Korea,

00:30:53.490 --> 00:30:56.780
and almost captured
the whole peninsula.

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.080
Americans came to the rescue
at the very last minute.

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:03.830
MacArthur was in Japan
with a division of troops,

00:31:03.830 --> 00:31:07.050
because this was just five years
after the end of World War II.

00:31:07.050 --> 00:31:10.370
The American troops pushed
the North Koreans right back

00:31:10.370 --> 00:31:14.000
up the peninsula and across
the 38th parallel, which

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.280
is the dividing line today,
as it had been before,

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:20.420
and were rapidly approaching
the Chinese border.

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:23.150
The Americans thought
it was inconceivable

00:31:23.150 --> 00:31:28.010
that China, which Mao was just
barely consolidating control

00:31:28.010 --> 00:31:30.800
of China after a
long civil war, would

00:31:30.800 --> 00:31:32.540
think of attacking the US.

00:31:32.540 --> 00:31:34.840
The US was the world supremo.

00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:37.280
Five years earlier, we
had dropped atomic bombs

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:41.450
on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, just
next door, to end World War II.

00:31:41.450 --> 00:31:44.930
So the idea that some little
country, 150th our size,

00:31:44.930 --> 00:31:47.000
would attack us
was inconceivable.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.400
They did, and lo and
behold, as I said,

00:31:49.400 --> 00:31:51.200
they beat us and
pushed us back down.

00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:54.410
That had nothing to do with any
Thucydides dynamic, for sure,

00:31:54.410 --> 00:31:55.910
for sure.

00:31:55.910 --> 00:31:59.720
In this case, if I
imagine we didn't

00:31:59.720 --> 00:32:02.720
have that Thucydides
dynamic, which

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:07.160
creates such a degree of
mistrust, and misunderstanding,

00:32:07.160 --> 00:32:13.070
and makes it so difficult
for adult behavior,

00:32:13.070 --> 00:32:16.250
I believe that we could,
China and America,

00:32:16.250 --> 00:32:19.470
resolve the North Korean
problem fairly easily.

00:32:19.470 --> 00:32:23.390
So in the book, I even try to
imagine an adult supervisor.

00:32:23.390 --> 00:32:26.250
I do this in my class at
Harvard from time to time.

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:29.050
I say, remember in
international relations,

00:32:29.050 --> 00:32:32.440
there are no adult supervisors.

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:33.750
This is a jungle.

00:32:33.750 --> 00:32:38.070
So there's nobody superior to
Donald Trump and Xi Jinping.

00:32:38.070 --> 00:32:41.640
Nobody that can just
say guys, hello.

00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:43.000
But let's imagine there were.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:45.240
So there's a
Martian strategists,

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:49.144
and she parachutes
down to Mar-a-Lago,

00:32:49.144 --> 00:32:51.310
and sits down, and says
guys, sit down for a minute.

00:32:51.310 --> 00:32:54.250
I'm just going to
tell you a few things.

00:32:54.250 --> 00:32:58.410
She could easily say this
problem can be solved.

00:32:58.410 --> 00:33:01.270
This is this little
pipsqueak country.

00:33:01.270 --> 00:33:03.910
It's going to drag the
two of you into a war?

00:33:03.910 --> 00:33:06.670
This would be stupid,
I mean really stupid.

00:33:06.670 --> 00:33:09.730
Now, you would have to
stand back a little bit.

00:33:09.730 --> 00:33:11.980
You probably would have to
adjust some things that you

00:33:11.980 --> 00:33:15.520
would otherwise imagine
you want to hold onto,

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:17.920
but let's talk about
ways of solving this.

00:33:17.920 --> 00:33:19.990
So if this was
Britain and the US,

00:33:19.990 --> 00:33:22.920
and the problem was
created by Ireland,

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:24.880
this would be easily solved.

00:33:24.880 --> 00:33:29.260
But in the cases in which you
have a Thucydides dynamic,

00:33:29.260 --> 00:33:33.790
external events are able to
have this exaggerated impact.

00:33:33.790 --> 00:33:34.730
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:34.730 --> 00:33:36.040
GRAHAM ALLISON: Please, sir.

00:33:36.040 --> 00:33:37.540
AUDIENCE: Your
book and your talk

00:33:37.540 --> 00:33:40.660
raises a whole set of
issues around China

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:43.030
and the US as actors.

00:33:43.030 --> 00:33:46.030
And one view is to think
of those issues assuming

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:48.600
that China and the US are
each monolithic actors.

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:51.280
I want to offer you a whole
collection of new issues,

00:33:51.280 --> 00:33:53.770
and let you take a pick
of which ones to tackle,

00:33:53.770 --> 00:33:56.320
that drill down a layer.

00:33:56.320 --> 00:33:58.150
The US is not monolithic.

00:33:58.150 --> 00:33:59.770
There's multiple power centers.

00:33:59.770 --> 00:34:02.710
There's multiple political
divisions and personalities,

00:34:02.710 --> 00:34:03.670
individually.

00:34:03.670 --> 00:34:06.400
I don't know about China, but
I assume there's something

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:08.409
below the surface there.

00:34:08.409 --> 00:34:10.300
When you talk about
we can solve this,

00:34:10.300 --> 00:34:13.776
we can learn the lessons
of history, who are the we?

00:34:13.776 --> 00:34:14.900
What are the power centers?

00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:16.510
Who needs to be educated?

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:19.750
And when you look at your
table of 16 cases of which

00:34:19.750 --> 00:34:21.820
went to war, and
which did not, what

00:34:21.820 --> 00:34:24.489
do we learn about the dynamics
of the internal politics

00:34:24.489 --> 00:34:25.989
and powers of those
nations and how

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:28.803
they contribute to the outcome?

00:34:28.803 --> 00:34:30.219
GRAHAM ALLISON:
You see me smiling

00:34:30.219 --> 00:34:35.260
because actually the
first book I ever wrote

00:34:35.260 --> 00:34:37.639
called "Essence of Decision:
Explaining the Cuban Missile

00:34:37.639 --> 00:34:40.929
Crises," which some of you
probably have looked at,

00:34:40.929 --> 00:34:44.620
makes up this argument
that while mostly we

00:34:44.620 --> 00:34:46.570
think about
international relations

00:34:46.570 --> 00:34:49.960
as if it were a game
between two monolithic chess

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:53.199
players, or billiard
balls, it's sometimes said,

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.830
that in fact
desegregating the actors

00:34:56.830 --> 00:35:00.460
to the large organizations
of which they're components,

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:04.510
or even in a third frame that
I offer, desegregating them

00:35:04.510 --> 00:35:07.805
into the individual human beings
who are players, who may have

00:35:07.805 --> 00:35:12.610
quite contrary views, are
also necessary if you're

00:35:12.610 --> 00:35:14.440
going to try to
understand the actions

00:35:14.440 --> 00:35:16.720
of this so-called monolith.

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:20.560
So this book has model one,
model two, and model three,

00:35:20.560 --> 00:35:22.720
and shows how by using
them, you can better

00:35:22.720 --> 00:35:25.600
understand what happened in
the Cuban Missile Crisis.

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:29.397
So in this case, I love the
idea of taking them and working

00:35:29.397 --> 00:35:29.980
your way down.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:31.150
The book does not do that.

00:35:31.150 --> 00:35:35.650
It says-- again the book
would not be 270 pages,

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:38.960
it would be considerably longer.

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:44.200
But in the case of
the US, obviously it

00:35:44.200 --> 00:35:47.470
matters a whole lot who is
the president, because he's

00:35:47.470 --> 00:35:50.630
the biggest player and gets
the biggest set of choices.

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:54.145
So if I go back to the
Cuban Missile Crisis

00:35:54.145 --> 00:35:56.560
just for that
analog, John Kennedy

00:35:56.560 --> 00:35:59.560
was president in his first--

00:35:59.560 --> 00:36:03.340
in April of 1961, four
months into office.

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:06.300
He authorized an
invasion of Cuba,

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:10.090
this so-called Bay of Pigs,
which was catastrophic.

00:36:10.090 --> 00:36:14.050
A bunch of Cuban
refugees trained by CIA

00:36:14.050 --> 00:36:18.430
and was CIA instructors
invaded Cuba and were captured.

00:36:18.430 --> 00:36:20.770
And it was a total mess.

00:36:20.770 --> 00:36:24.070
A year and a half later, in
the Cuban Missile Crisis,

00:36:24.070 --> 00:36:27.070
when the US found the
Soviet Union installing

00:36:27.070 --> 00:36:30.130
nuclear tipped
missiles in Cuba, he

00:36:30.130 --> 00:36:33.490
conducted an exercise,
which was still

00:36:33.490 --> 00:36:39.430
one of the great performances
and brilliant imaginative type

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:40.870
diplomacy.

00:36:40.870 --> 00:36:45.730
But if the Kennedy
of the first year--

00:36:45.730 --> 00:36:49.000
if the Cuban Missile Crisis had
occurred in John F. Kennedy's

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.790
first year, there's
no question whatever

00:36:51.790 --> 00:36:54.970
we would have gone to nuclear
war with the Soviet Union.

00:36:54.970 --> 00:36:58.350
Because a novice,
even a novice who's

00:36:58.350 --> 00:37:02.100
been a senator, trying to
operate the US government

00:37:02.100 --> 00:37:05.150
doesn't really understand
how things work.

00:37:05.150 --> 00:37:06.690
Now, in the case
of Trump, you have

00:37:06.690 --> 00:37:11.490
a person who doesn't know
anything about the government

00:37:11.490 --> 00:37:15.610
before, and having to learn
entirely new situations.

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:17.160
I say you have him.

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:20.860
Then you have the principal
players around him.

00:37:20.860 --> 00:37:23.520
And I think there's a lot
of comfort in the fact

00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:26.280
that in H.R. McMaster,
the National Security

00:37:26.280 --> 00:37:29.460
Adviser, you've got a
seasoned professional who's

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:32.820
very independent minded,
and Jim Mattis, who

00:37:32.820 --> 00:37:37.260
we saw in the video, you've
got a seasoned warrior, who's

00:37:37.260 --> 00:37:38.650
very professional.

00:37:38.650 --> 00:37:40.650
In Tillerson,
you've got a person

00:37:40.650 --> 00:37:43.320
who's got a significant
international vision.

00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:45.540
So they're are also players.

00:37:45.540 --> 00:37:47.895
You then have the
military establishment.

00:37:47.895 --> 00:37:50.760
The military establishment
has developed capabilities

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:52.410
that are just magical.

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:54.180
I'm a Defense Department type.

00:37:54.180 --> 00:37:58.890
So the US has the
finest military

00:37:58.890 --> 00:38:00.750
that the world has ever seen.

00:38:00.750 --> 00:38:04.140
Any target, anywhere in the
world that Google can find,

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:05.400
we can destroy.

00:38:05.400 --> 00:38:07.410
And actually, we
can do a better job

00:38:07.410 --> 00:38:11.450
than that in terms
of the coordinates.

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:13.230
So that's for destroying things.

00:38:13.230 --> 00:38:17.640
So we have a whole
toolbox of hammers,

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:20.460
and we can nail any target.

00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:23.580
Unfortunately, most of the
problems in the world cannot be

00:38:23.580 --> 00:38:26.780
solved as if they were
a nail with a hammer.

00:38:26.780 --> 00:38:28.110
That's a problem.

00:38:28.110 --> 00:38:30.540
That's a problem when you
end up having your best

00:38:30.540 --> 00:38:34.290
hope in the structure of
the government's decision

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:37.350
making military people, because
military people or defense

00:38:37.350 --> 00:38:40.680
types come thinking look,
excuse me, we have hammers,

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:42.750
we need to find a nail.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:44.970
So I would say that's
for desegregating

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:45.760
the US side of it.

00:38:45.760 --> 00:38:51.240
On the Chinese side, Xi Jinping,
If we just take the year ahead,

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:55.290
he is the Supremo in an
authoritarian system.

00:38:55.290 --> 00:39:01.050
But it's not totalitarian,
and not everything,

00:39:01.050 --> 00:39:02.850
not all power runs through him.

00:39:02.850 --> 00:39:05.700
His big idea this
year is getting

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:08.460
through what's called the
19th Party Congress, which

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:11.700
is an event that will occur
this fall, where he's going

00:39:11.700 --> 00:39:15.000
to win a second term of
office, a second five-year term

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:16.080
as president.

00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:18.630
But more importantly,
he's going to try

00:39:18.630 --> 00:39:21.210
to put in place a
standing committee, which

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:23.640
are seven people
who were supposed

00:39:23.640 --> 00:39:26.160
to be the collective
leadership, even though he's

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:28.420
pretty much excluded them now.

00:39:28.420 --> 00:39:32.820
And he's called the COE,
the Chief of Everything.

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:36.000
So he tries to run everything,
and all the power verticals

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:37.150
are going to him.

00:39:37.150 --> 00:39:39.780
He's going to have a standing
committee, in which there

00:39:39.780 --> 00:39:42.540
is no obvious successor.

00:39:42.540 --> 00:39:45.750
So that he'll be able
to look at runway of 15

00:39:45.750 --> 00:39:49.800
or even 20 years, because he
has an agenda that he thinks

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:51.540
is going to be that long to run.

00:39:51.540 --> 00:39:54.000
So you would have
to desegregate that.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.730
You look at this, and you
say, in this structure,

00:39:56.730 --> 00:40:00.210
is there anybody who thinks
war on the Korean peninsula

00:40:00.210 --> 00:40:00.960
is a good idea?

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:01.800
No.

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:02.790
Is this a good thing?

00:40:02.790 --> 00:40:03.810
Yes.

00:40:03.810 --> 00:40:06.030
So there's not one
person in China

00:40:06.030 --> 00:40:08.370
who thinks war with
the US is a good idea.

00:40:08.370 --> 00:40:09.180
That's great.

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:11.080
Nor in the US, with China.

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:14.420
So we could work our way
down this piece by piece,

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:17.160
and I'd be happy to
talk about it after,

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:20.700
because it's a topic that
excites my imagination.

00:40:20.700 --> 00:40:22.500
But in this book,
I try to do it--

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:25.544
I just have to do it
at the first level.

00:40:25.544 --> 00:40:27.910
Please sir--

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:31.420
AUDIENCE: Not everybody at
Google was born after 1990.

