00:47:00.810 --> 00:47:04.510
Under conditions of mutual
assured destruction,

00:47:04.510 --> 00:47:10.850
can parties take risks that
don't have a certainty attached

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:15.240
to them, especially if the other
party is prepared to yield?

00:47:15.240 --> 00:47:17.720
In fact, I discuss this a
little bit in the book about--

00:47:17.720 --> 00:47:20.930
this is basically, if you
model it in game theory,

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:22.610
it's a chicken game.

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:26.030
If we both know that the
collision between the two cars

00:47:26.030 --> 00:47:28.610
will be destruction,
then each of us

00:47:28.610 --> 00:47:31.430
have an incentive to swerve.

00:47:31.430 --> 00:47:34.340
And if I think you're more
likely to swerve than I am,

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:36.140
then I don't need to swerve.

00:47:36.140 --> 00:47:39.710
And then under those
conditions, occasionally we

00:47:39.710 --> 00:47:42.140
end up with a collision
that kills us all.

00:47:42.140 --> 00:47:44.870
So that's the path on this.

